segments.text: a quiz or a question on a quiz in a geology course that I was taking.
Somehow or another metal got involved and I said all this scrap metal that we've been shipping over to Japan, I was loaded in 1941, in the spring of 1941, will come back in the way of bombs.
And I remember answering the question on my geology quiz.
And so I don't know.
Of course, we didn't know about Pearl Harbor.
But it was fairly obvious.
And then, my lord, you get ordered to active duty before you graduate.
Now, with a straight face, what war opposition groups were there on the campus?
None.
None.
Let's go to a lighter topic.
How did a young Aggie get a date in your undergraduate years?
Well there was somebody back in your hometown that you would invite down.
Or if you happened to know some gal from Bryan.
Or you had none.
And to what activities would she normally be in?
Well you've got, of course the big thing you've seen in years, you've seen her ring dance.
But then RV holidays, another.
And then they had various balls during the year.
Each regiment had one, as I recall.
I don't remember ever having a date on the campus until I was a senior.
But that was just me and others.
they weren't bringing down trainloads of Tessies in those days.
A lot of gals came down from CIA.
I've heard stories later about moose pots and beast buckets.
Those are unfamiliar terms.
Who got stuck with the worst moose?
Or which girl got stuck with the worst beast?
I never heard that.
If a young woman was on campus in
for a weekend, where did she stay?
In a dorm or some privileged view at Aggieland Inn.
Would y'all clear out a dorm?
Yes, vacate.
Like in Puryear, for example, they had ramps.
Just clear out two or three ramps.
And they were very strictly observed.
Was a young man without a date allowed to go to one of these dances?
Sure he could go.
And how often did a pretty young lady get cut in on?
Often.
And what do you think was the impression that Aggies made on these young ladies?
Well, you could hear all kinds of stories after the fact.
I've talked to a lot of women since 1941.
They tell you I used to go with A&M and loved it and loved it.
Yeah.
That's what I've heard.
That's what I've heard.
Yeah, they like to come.
Well, why not?
They were treated royally.
And how did the young man and young woman dress for these dances?
Well, of course, we wore uniform and ladies wore evening gowns.
Were there any big-time bands that came?
Sure.
Plenty.
Such as?
Well, whatever.
I can't remember.
Artie Shaw...
Even the fellow that says a one, a two, a three, champagne music.
Lawrence Welk?
Yeah, he was there.
We had him for an RV dance, playing beautiful music.
The major bands, the Dorsey band, everyone.
And these were in Sabeasa?
In Sabeasa.
And what was the conduct pattern of people?
How did everybody behave?
Very well.
And could the dance go all night?
No.
No, it happened at midnight, one o'clock, whatever, curfew.
Let's see.
You didn't have a car.
No.
Did anybody in your outfit have one that everybody used?
No.
Describe the community around the campus.
What was College Station then?
Where was it?
What was it?
Well, College Station in those days essentially was, to some extent, at Northgate,
And on each of the two corners there, there were drug stores.
And then Honick Boot Shop was down there, and Aggieland Photographers or whatever, they were down there.
No eating places at all.
Was the movie there?
The campus theater?
The campus theater was there.
Yeah, there was a movie.
As a matter of fact, I was the director of Aggie Tone News.
Tell me about Aggie Tone News.
Well...
Somebody had an idea that we should produce a newsreel, special events.
And of course it was just, it was video.
Yeah, you had no sound to it or anything, but a picture of a parade, a halftime ceremony, a football game or whatever.
And there weren't very many.
We only did it for maybe a half a dozen times.
would write out the script for it, and they played them at that theater down there.
And you set up in a booth someplace, and while the thing is being shown, you're talking.
So when I say the director of Aggietone News, I was the only one that spoke to it, while it was going on.
Was this a paying?
No.
Director of Narration.
Ah, that would do it.
That's it.
Director of Narration of Agaton.
Was there anything at Southgate then?
Maidley's Pharmacy, was it there yet?
No.
Okay.
Southgate, Southgate.
Immediately south of Project Houses?
Nothing.
Okay.
Nothing.
Okay.
And Old Army Lou wasn't yet in business, was he?
Yes, I believe he was.
Oh.
I believe, maybe I'm confusing it
with after the war.
Where did the faculty live?
They lived south toward Navasota.
That's where the first residential district that I can remember, plus some north.
Were there some residences on campus?
No.
Yes, the president had a house, and Baratracks Bolton had a house.
He was the dean.
People said, the dean of men?
I said, no, he was just the dean.
But... Did y'all have a nickname for Gilchrist, dean of engineering?
I didn't have one.
He would just give the... T.O.
Walton was the president of the great...
Nickname for him?
Just, I don't remember any.
He just was much respected and admired.
Describe him.
Well, he was just a very low-key fellow.
Very friendly.
Big little, normal sized man as I remember.
One big man on campus was Ike Ashburn.
And he officed down in the, what we called the, we called it the, not the system building, I forget now what we called it, the beautiful Greek,
The one down east, on the east side?
Okay, in the new Jack Williams building.
It will be.
That's correct.
But Ike Ashburn was... Do you remember what his task was?
Well, he was sort of a PR man, an administrative assistant of a type.
The guy must have weighed 300 pounds.
He was just a huge fellow.
He had an office in Austin and was in charge of Texas roadways or something.
He was a politician of a type.
But he was a great favorite, and he taught a course, a one hour course to seniors on nothing.
And you made an A in it.
I mean, it just was one of those giveaways, the only giveaway I remember.
And he attended various things.
For example, I was the master of ceremonies at the senior ring dance.
And when I introduced him, I said,
Our next guest is living evidence that an army travels on its stomach.
It is with pleasure I present to you Colonel Ike Ashburn.
Everybody just roared, including Ike.
Oh, great.
He stood up and came to the mic, and he said, Anybody as big as I am that made a speech on an occasion like this ought to have things thrown at you.
So thank you very much for the invitation.
And he went over and sat down.
So everybody got a big kick out of it.
But I said, living evidence, proof that an army travels on its own.
But he was known as Colonel Ike.
Was the commandant important?
Oh, yeah.
The commandant and the professor of military science and tactics were different, too.
Who was the commandant?
Colonel George F. Moore.
was there and he left at the end of my junior year and a fella came and took his place my senior year and everybody hated his guts.
George Moore, George F. Moore was an Aggie, class of 23, something like that.
Later became a major general and was on Corregidor.
Where?
George F. Moore.
The Commandant just performed
ministerial functions and had nothing to do really with the military.
Let's see, student indulgences, court trips, a typical Aggie football day in College Station, or maybe football weekend.
Well, you had the practice on Friday night, went to class Saturday, oftentimes got out at noon time, and you just walked over to the ballpark and
The freshmen sat down at the bottom and back of them the sophomores and back of them the juniors and back of them the seniors.
Wait, the freshmen sat nearest the field?
Yes.
They stood nearest the field.
That's right.
The sophomores standing in back of them and then the juniors and then the seniors.
Did y'all march in?
No.
Did the band march in?
Maybe.
What about halftime?
Always marched.
Describe, make believe I'd never seen an Aggie band

at halftime about this farmed up at the north end of the field like they do today and and marched what what jazz what jazz and rock music did they play none of course oh and in those days you see the first reveille was there oh hey describe the first rebel okay she was just a dog a mongrel dog
What color?
Brown.
She was there when I got there, but she'd only been there a couple of years as I recall.
The story is really sort of hazy.
Somewhere or another she was injured, and Corman coming back from a weekend trip someplace,
either saw her get hurt or caused her to be hurt or whatever out in the roadway, and they brought her back to Constitution.
I know that she was there when I got there, and she'd been there about two or three years, but no longer.
She was not kept by a unit.
She was an 800-pound gorilla.
She did what she wanted to do, and she seemed to know.
which beds were occupied by freshmen.
Because if she came into a room and got into a freshman's bed, he got out.
And she also ate at Sabisa.
Now, were there other dogs?
No.
No.
And she marched with the band, not on a leash.
And that band, she went and made court trips.
And that band would be out there and they would each say, just counter march.
And she's right there in the middle of them and never interfered with a single marcher.
Did she bark at the right times?
Yes.
She was spoiled a lot.
But she marched with the band and never interfered with anybody.
When the new part of the campus, Queen Mudd Junior, what we called it the new area, now the quad,
When the band went over there, the band had a responsibility for her own courthouse.
And so they took her over there to the new area.
And she stayed not one night because it was a new area to her.
So she came back to the old area.
And did she sleep in a...
In wherever she wanted to.
And was it quite often different?
Yes, but over in the old area.
She spent an awful lot of time around the Y.
That was very familiar to her.
Law and Furrier and Mitchell and Hart.
If you could guess about her ancestry, type of dog, what do you think?
A mix of goodness knows what.
I really don't know.
I really don't know.
No, she was a medium-sized dog.
And she was just spoiled rotten.
She'd just look at you.
Come here, Red.
Come here, Red.
I'm sorry I interrupted you.
Thanks.
It works okay.
Thanks.
The yells, you all stood during the game.
Were yells similar then to now?
Yes.
Most of the yells were the same.
They've got some different ones now.
Were there some that were done then maybe in bad taste?
No.
OK. No.
And none of this beat the hell out of that.
We tried when they started doing that.
When I say we, a number of us, me and him, spoke to them and suggested they abandon Yale.
They just thumbed their nose at us.
Well, and I tried to tell them, too, that's a vulgar gesture.
It really is, and they know what it is.
And I remember when it started.
I remember.
We tried to discourage it, and they paid no attention to it.
But we didn't have that yell.
We used to when a substitution was different in those days.
A player came out like Marion Pugh now was a quarterback, and we'd say, we'd spell it out.
A-U-G-H, Pugh, Pugh, Pugh.
So if somebody had played well, they'd spell her name out.
All right, when the game was over, and... Crashman went after the elevator.
And where did they get thrown?
They got thrown in...
There was some place close to Military Walk.
Yeah, the north end of Military Walk near Sabisa, I think.
I guess, yeah.
Fish Pond, they called it.
Of the various...
I'll tell you another thing that happened.
This also happened even after the war.
We picked up the visiting football team, carried them off the field.
Oh, but not in anger, but you mean carried him off on his shoulders.
That's right.
That's right.
Bear Bryant, he said that's what influenced him to leave Kentucky and come to A&M.
Kentucky came over there and played, and they picked up his football team and carried him off the field.
We've always been the best sportsmen when the other side's song is being sung, and none of this business of running out on a field while he and him are singing.
Those things still anger me to this day, and they're deliberate, absolutely deliberate.
But we used to win the sportsmanship award year after year after year because we were great sportsmen.
What were some of your football game memories?
Oh, well, you see, we were national champions when I was there.
Which games do you remember with greatest joy?
Every one of my junior and all but one of my senior years.
I remember of course the first game I ever saw at Kyle Field A&M played Sam Houston and Dick Todd was running back and took the kickoff.
Ran for a touchdown, first time I ever saw him touch the ball.
Played a little bit for the Washington Redskins after that.
My junior year, you see, we won everything.
And went out and played Tulane in the Sugar Bowl and won that game and were 19, national champion in 1939.
Then 1940, 41, we won nine games in a row.
And we were going on to the Rose Bowl, just Austin stood in the way.
Cuz in those days they didn't have that contract between the Big Ten and the Pac-10.
And we were on our way to the Rose Bowl, and we got beat seven to nothing in Austin.
They scored on the third play of the game, and that was the only score in the game.
And it was a sad, sad day.
We didn't leave the stands after the game, and the band was playing taps.
And those damn T-7s came down there and interrupted the thing.
Could easily have had a fight right then and there.
Among the football players, did you have some favorite acquaintances?
Not really.
Jim Thomason.
was active in the Corps, I believe was a cadet major.
My senior year, one of the freshmen in my outfit was named Martin Ruby.
He played pro ball.
They just sort of led their own lives separately, but Jim Thomason was the fullback.
And he was in the Corps.
I remember Chip Rowder, you see,
Kimbrough, classmate.
Willie Conacher, classmate.
Marion Pugh, classmate.
Chip Rout, classmate.
Marshall Robinette, classmate.
Joe Boyd was in the class of 40.
He was a great favorite with the Colts.
He was a nice guy.
Turned out to be a Baptist preacher.
But they were sort of... Did athletes go to class?
I don't know what they did.
Did they graduate?
I don't know what they did.
I think they did in those days.
I think they did.
Let's see.
You went to commencements, but you didn't get to go to your own.
Did you go to some the first three years?
Yeah.
Were there any important campus visitors, big name visitors you remember seeing or hearing?
Other than military people, I don't remember any.
I really don't.
There was no white electors series, special MSC functions.
No, and the president didn't come, and John Nance Garner didn't come.
He could have, but I don't remember it, and I rather doubt it.
Yeah, Pershing didn't come.
No, not that I'm aware of.
Let's see.
As you're preparing to leave the campus and following your graduation, what sort of world did you think you were entering?
What did you think was it?
Well, I just knew that war was imminent.
And sure enough, in six months, Pearl Harbor happened.
And on my 2015, I can remember looking at it.
I can see it today on this occupation student.

So five years later, when I had an opportunity to integrate in the regular army before the war started, then when I came back from the Pacific, I would extend another invitation to integrate in the regular army, and I turned that down.
And then I had a third time later to do it, and I turned that down.
Even the President of the United States offered me the Undersecretary of the Army's job, which I turned down when I sat on the Federal Trade Commission.
All right.
How, as you left with the possibility of war, how well prepared did you think you were for that responsibility?
Well, I thought I could do anything.
Hell, I was 21 years old and second lieutenant, single.
I was ready to go fight the Japanese.
I was madder than hell after Pearl Harbor.
The whole country was mad.
What's the difference?
We had identified enemies.
Hitler and Hirohito.
and told Joe who rode a white horse that he was going to ride his horse down Pennsylvania.
Well he never did.
He never did.
See today's young people don't understand that at all.
And also because we really haven't had a war for a long time.
Even Vietnam was minute compared to World War II.
Yeah, the Korean War.
But it was different.
And so that we are farther now
from World War II than you and I were from the Spanish-American War.
See, because it's 42, three years from the Spanish-American War to the Second World War.
All right, now we're 52 years from World War II.
Let's see.
There were some interviews that had taken place on the campus for civilian jobs.
I was interviewed by...
an insurance company, and somebody else.
I can't remember now.
But, of course, when the orders came, I was delighted.
Getting out of A&M and not having to go out into the civilian world, which the country's still in depression, would have been a tough, tough thing to do.
And it just was made easy with this military order.
As you left, what were your financial resources?
Well, I had none.
I had none.
I borrowed $100 my freshman year from this one man, and $100 my sophomore year from this same man.
Then the Rotary Club had a program where you could borrow $200, but only juniors and seniors.
So I borrowed $200 my junior year and $200 my senior year.
Of course I worked in the summer, but I had nothing.
I had no car.
But Bryan Motor Company, they were a Ford dealer, said that they would give you a thousand dollar graduation present if you were going on active duty.
And it could be used as a down payment
for a Ford automobile.
So I went to Bryan Motor Company and I got a Ford Club Coupe, they called it.
A sporty kind of a vehicle, first car I ever owned.
Never had one growing up, family didn't have one, mother didn't.
And they found the car cost $972.
Really it was $1,072, but it cost $972.
And I went to what was called the United States Automobile Association at the time, USAA, and got some insurance on the car.
And the motor and the Ford company made arrangements for us to get a monthly loan.
I forget the payments were $30 a month, something like that.
The second lieutenant didn't make a whole lot of money, $125 a month.
cost $18 a month for subsistence, and yet your regimental officer's club cost $30 a month.
But nevertheless, the money was pretty scarce.
It was tougher than hell, as a matter of fact.
A first lieutenant made $166.67.
Don't ask me why that was, but that was a whole lot more than a second lieutenant made.
A captain made $200.
A major $270.
The lieutenant colonel, $310 a month.
Now, when you graduated, did you still owe those loans, that money?
Sure.
So in the summer, you had had a job, but you hadn't made enough to pay off those loans.
That's right.
When did you pay them off?
As soon as I started drawing $125 a month.
First thing I did was pay them.
I don't owe any of them today, as we sit and talk.
I owe no man.
How do you feel in hindsight about that man that loaned you that money?
Well, forever grateful, because he was no relation.
He just had a big printing company, and I lived in a house about two blocks from his printing plant, so it was something less than River Oaks.
As a matter of fact, I lived two blocks from the railroad tracks, and his man's name was Loudon.
and the printing company whose name was Stafford Loudon and his son, and I graduated from the same high school at the same time.
And I just went to him and told him I wanted to go to college, and I had no way.
And he wanted to, at the end of the year, he wanted to see the report cards.
So I reported to him.
He wanted to know what I was doing, what was going on.
I'm sure I was not the only one, but I never knew if there were others.
Because you never hear anything like that from him.
Did you sign a contract?
No.
No.
No, signed nothing.
Did he lend money only to Aggies?
I have no idea what his activities were.
I never asked.
Doesn't sound like there's any ulterior motive on his part at all.
None.
Did you pay him interest?
No.
No.
Just paid him the $100.
Let's jump back.
The student body at that time, how diverse was it in the background of the students?
Mostly middle class America, I would say, and lower middle class.
From big cities, country, towns, what?
Mostly from the country, small towns.
It was not until post-World War II that we ever got a graduate from Memorial High School near Houston.
I remember the first one.
Did, were there- San Antonio was a big A&M town.
Were there any Hispanic students?
A few, but mostly from foreign countries.
Okay, and how were they treated?
Very well.
We had some from Puerto Rico.
I had a Puerto Rican in my outfit, Francisco Salvador Palantaba.
Did you all have a nickname for those Hispanics?
No.
Were there any Jewish students?
Yes.
How were they treated?
Very well.
Were there any nicknames for them?
No, not that I'm aware of.
I just can remember at the announcement at Evening Mess, once a month the Hillel Club would meet and somebody would comment about it.
So you don't forget you got a meeting tonight.
To that extent there was, but you never would say it to me.
There were no Jewish boys in Miami.
Were there any Asian, students of Asian ancestry?
Yeah, there were a couple of Japs there when we were there.
One in a farming family down here close to Houston.
Do you remember the name?
I did at one time, but I've forgotten it now.
Was it Kishi?
I don't remember.
Let me turn it off.
You said there were two Japanese?
Yes, I can't remember.
One was a great favorite.
You don't remember any Chinese?
Not a single one.
Middle Eastern?
No.
Did it matter that a student was Catholic?
I don't think it made any difference to anybody what their religion was or their faith.
All right, that's where I wanted to hit.
Why?
Well, I don't know.
Maybe it was... What determined a student's importance among other students?
Whether he was a senior or a junior or a sophomore, if you were a freshman.
Let me tell you.
A&M is the most democratic institute.
The Army is very democratic.
I can't tell you how many times I've come out.
